{{Infobox ethnic group |group = Nepalis in South Korea |population = 70,015 (2013)<ref name="Immigration.go.kr">{{citation|url=http://www.immigration.go.kr/HP/COM/bbs_003/ListShowData.do?strNbodCd=noti0096&strWrtNo=124&strAnsNo=A&strOrgGbnCd=104000&strRtnURL=IMM_6050&strAllOrgYn=N&strThisPage=1&strFilePath=imm/|title=Total Nepalese in Korea Southpublisher=Ministry of Justice|publication-place=South Korea|year=2009|accessdate=2011-03-21|page=262}}</ref> |popplace = [[Uijeongbu]]{{·}}[[Ansan]]{{·}}[[Gimhae]]{{·}}[[Gwangju]]<ref name="KoreaTimes20091023">{{citation|url=http://www.koreatimes.co.kr/www/news/nation/2009/12/211_54164.html|title=10,000 Nepalese Diaspora Emerging in Korea|periodical=[[The Korea Times]]|date=2009-10-23|accessdate=2010-08-23}}</ref> |langs = [[Korean language|Korean]]{{·}}[[Maithili language|Maithili]]{{•}}[[Nepali language|Nepali]] |rels = [[Hinduism]]{{·}}[[Buddhism]]{{·}}[[Christianity]] |related-c = [[People of Nepal|Nepali people]] }}
'''Nepalese in South Korea''' comprise [[Koreans|Korean Citizens]] and [[Nepalis|Nepalese]] migrant workers, including temporary expatriates and permanent residents, as well as their locally born descendants of either [[Koreans|Korean]] or [[Nepalis|Nepalese]] nationality. The [[Nepalis|Nepalese]] in South Korea are mainly of four distinct ethnic groups : [[Bahun|Bahun (Brahmins)]], [[Chhetri|Chhetri (Rajputs)]], [[Madhesi people|Madhesis]] and [[indigenous people|Janjati]]s.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://arkonetwork.com/news/nepal/nepali-workers-south-korea-provide-aid-rss/|title=Korea Madhesi Society to inspect condition of migrant Madhesi Victims in korea}}</ref>
==Migration history== The first wave of Nepalese immigration began in the late 1980s. After Nepal restored its democracy in the 1990s, labour laws were changed to allow Nepalese youths to go abroad in search of work.<ref name="KoreaTimes20091023"/> The Nepalese community in South Korea thus consists primarily of migrant workers, but also has large numbers of students as well as Nepalese women married to South Korean men they met through international matchmaking agencies.<ref name="KoreaTimes20091023"/><ref>{{citation|periodical=Daily News and Analysis|title=Nepali girls sold as 'brides' to old South Koreans|date=2009-02-15|accessdate=2010-08-23|url=http://www.dnaindia.com/world/report_nepali-girls-sold-as-brides-to-old-south-koreans_1230977}}</ref> The Nepali government are attempting to induce Nepali workers staying illegally in South Korea (roughly 2,500 {{asof|2010|lc=on}}) to return home, in hopes that the South Korean government will increase its intake of Nepali workers in future years.<ref>{{citation|url=http://www.koreatimes.co.kr/www/news/nation/2010/07/120_59591.html|date=2010-01-24|accessdate=2010-08-26|title=Nepal to Roll Back 2,500 Illegal Workers From Korea|periodical=The Korea Times|last=Giri|first=Anil}}</ref>
==Culture== The Nepalese community managed to keep their traditions alive while living in South Korea. Nepalese festivals such as [[Tihar (festival)|Tihar]], [[Dasain]] and [[Teej]] are celebrated throughout the country.<ref name="KoreaTimes20091023"/>
==Organisations== The Non-Resident Nepali Association of Korea is one organisation for Nepalese people living in South Korea. In 2010, they opened a shelter in [[Dongdaemun-gu]], [[Seoul]] to provide charitable assistance for Nepalese who become unemployed or otherwise face difficulties.<ref>{{citation|title=Nepal house inaugurated in SKorea|date=2010-08-18|accessdate=2010-08-23|periodical=República|url=http://www.myrepublica.com/portal/index.php?action=news_details&news_id=22322}}</ref> Another organisation, aimed specifically at [[international student]]s, is the [[Society_of_Nepalese_Students_in_Korea-SONSIK|Society of Nepalese Students in Korea (SONSIK)]], established in 2004.<ref>{{citation|url=http://www.imaeil.com/sub_news/sub_news_view.php?news_id=34157&yy=2010|periodical=Maeil Shinmun|date=2010-08-23|accessdate=2010-08-23|title=전국 네팔 유학생회 대구서 모임, 한국과 학술교류 통해 유대 강화|last=Hwang|first=Su-yeong}}</ref> South Korea's multilingual Migrant Workers' Television was founded by Nepali migrant worker [[Minod Moktan]] (Minu), a human rights activist who stayed in South Korea as an illegal alien for nearly 18 years before his deportation in October 2009.<ref>{{citation|url=http://www.koreatimes.co.kr/www/news/nation/2009/12/117_54223.html|date=2009-10-25|accessdate=2010-08-26|title=Nepalese Activist Deported|last=Bae|first=Ji-sook|periodical=The Korea Times}}</ref>
